window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2011>1>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2011","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"MOTION : SOLID FRICTION","question":"You are provided with a wooden block to which a hook is fixed, set of masses, spring balance and other necessary materials. Using the diagram above as a guide, carry out the following instructions.    (i) Record the mass  mo  indicated on the wooden block.  (ii) Place the block on the table.  (iii) Attach the spring balance to the hook.  (iv) Pull the spring balance horizontally with a gradual increase in force until the block just starts to move.  Record the spring balance reading F.  (v) Repeat the procedure by placing in turn mass m = 200, 400, 600 and 800 g on top of the block.  In each case, read and record the corresponding value of F.  (vi) Evaluate  M  =  mo +  m and R = M100\\frac{M}{100}100M\u200b in  each case.  (vii) Tabulate your readings.  (viii) Plot a graph with  F on the vertical axis and  R  on the horizontal axis.  (ix) Determine the slope, s, of the graph.  (x) State  two  precautions taken to ensure accurate results. [21 marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"mo = 350 g    Table of Value / observation    m(g)F(N)M = (mo + m) (g)R = M100\\frac{M}{100}100M\u200b(g)2002.00550.005.504003.00750.007.506004.00950.009.508005.001150.0011.50        s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 4\u221229.5\u22125.5\\frac{4-2}{9.5-5.5}9.5\u22125.54\u22122\u200b = 24\\frac{2}{4}42\u200b = 0.5    Precautions:  1. I carefully avoided parallax error by viewing the scale on the spring balance directly at eye level to ensure accurate readings.    2. I gently tapped the wood/load to prevent it from sticking to the table, ensuring smooth and consistent measurements.    3. I ensured that the spring balance was properly calibrated and zeroed before each measurement to avoid systematic errors.    4. I placed the apparatus on a stable, flat surface to prevent unintended shifts or vibrations during the experiment.    5. I repeated each measurement multiple times and averaged the results to reduce the influence of random errors.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2011>1>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2011","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"MOTION : SOLID FRICTION","question":"Define coefficient of static friction. [2 marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The coefficient of static friction is a dimensionless constant that represents the ratio of the maximum static frictional force between two surfaces to the normal (perpendicular) force acting between them. It indicates how much resistance to motion there is before the surfaces start to slide against each other.  Mathematically, it is expressed as:    \u03bcs \u200b= FsN\\frac{F_{s}}{N}NFs\u200b\u200b\u200b\u200b    where:  \u03bcs\u200b is the coefficient of static friction,  Fs\u200b is the maximum static frictional force, and  N is the normal force.    The coefficient of static friction depends on the nature and texture of the contact surfaces.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2011>1>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2011","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"MOTION : SOLID FRICTION","question":"A block of wood of mass 0.5 kg is pulled horizontally on a table by a force of 2.5 N. Calculate the coefficient of static friction between the two surfaces. (g = 10 ms-2). [2 marks]    (Provide your answer to 1 d.p)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Mass of the block of wood, m = 0.5 kg    Force, Fs = 2.5 N    Normal reaction, N = mg = 0.5 \u00d7 10 = 5 N    Coefficient of static friction, \u03bcs  =  FsN\\frac{F_{s}}{N}NFs\u200b\u200b = 2.55\\frac{2.5}{5}52.5\u200b = 0.5","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2011>2>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2011","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"Use the diagram above as a guide to carry out the following experiment.  (i) Trace the outline ABCD of the rectangular glass prism on the drawing paper provided.  (ii) Remove the prism. Select a point  N  on AB such that AN is about one quarter of AB.  (iii) Draw the normal LNM.  Also draw a line RN to make an angle \u03b8 = 75\u00b0 with AB at  N .  (iv) Fix two pins at P1 and P2 on line RN. Replace the prism on its outline.  (v) Fix two other pins at P3 and P4 such that they appear to be in a straight line with the images of the pins at P1 and P2 when viewed through the prism from side DC.  (vi) Remove the prism and the pins at P3 and P4 Draw a line to join P3 and P4.  (vii) Produce line P4 P3 to meet the line DC at O. Draw a line to join NO.  (viii) Measure and record the values of MO and NO.  (ix) Evaluate \u0444 = MONO\\frac{MO}{NO}NOMO\u200b  and  cos \u03b8.  (x) Repeat the procedure for four other values of \u03b8 = 65\u00b0, 55\u00b0, 45\u00b0 and 35\u00b0. In  each  case, evaluate \u0444 and cos \u03b8  (xi) Tabulate your readings.  (xii) Plot a graph with cos \u03b8 on the vertical axis and \u0444 on the horizontal axis.  (xiii) Determine the slope, s, of the graph.  (xiv) Sate two precautions taken to ensure accurate results. [21 marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Table of values / observation    \u03b80MO(cm)NO(cm)\u0444 = MONO\\frac{MO}{NO}NOMO\u200bcos \u03b8 7501.16.25.60.25886502.06.43.20.42265502.56.62.60.57364503.46.82.00.70713503.97.21.80.8192        slope, s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 0.775\u22120.31.5\u22125\\frac{0.775-0.3}{1.5-5}1.5\u221250.775\u22120.3\u200b = 0.475\u22123.5\\frac{0.475}{-3.5}\u22123.50.475\u200b = -0.1357 = -0.14    Precautions:  1. I ensured that all pins were positioned vertically and firmly to avoid any misalignment that could affect accuracy.    2. I used sharp pencils to create neat and precise traces, ensuring clarity and consistency in measurements.    3. I maintained a reasonable spacing between pins to improve measurement accuracy and prevent clustering.    4. I avoided parallax error by reading the protractor directly at eye level for each measurement.    5. I placed the apparatus on a stable surface to prevent vibrations or shifts that could interfere with measurement consistency.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2011>2>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2011","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"State Snell's law of refraction. [2 marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Snell's law states that the ratio of the sine of the angle of incidence to the sine of the angle of refraction is constant for any two given media. This constant is known as the refractive index. Mathematically, it can be expressed as:    n = sin\u2061(i)sin\u2061(r)\\frac{\\sin{\\left(i\\right)}}{\\sin{\\left(r\\right)}}sin(r)sin(i)\u200b","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2011>2>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2011","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"Calculate the critical angle for the glass prism used in the experiment above if its refractive index is 1.5. [2 marks]    (Provide your answer without the degree sign and to 1 d.p)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Refractive index, n = 1.5    sin C = 1n\\frac{1}{n}n1\u200b    sin C = 11.5\\frac{1}{1.5}1.51\u200b    sin C = 0.6667    C = sin-1(0.6667)     C = 41.80\u00b0    The critical angle = 41.8\u00b0","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2011>3>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2011","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CURRENT ELECTRICITY","question":"You are provided with cells, a potentiometer, an ammeter, a voltmeter, a bulb, a key, a jockey and other necessary materials.  (i) Measure and record the emf, E, of the battery.  (ii) Set-up a circuit as shown in the diagram above.  (iii) Close the key K and use jockey to make a firm contact at J on the potentiometer wire such such that PJ = x = 10 cm.  (iv) Take and record the voltmeter reading  and the corresponding ammeter reading I  (v) Evaluate log V and log I  (vi) Repeat the procedure for other values of x = 20, 30, 40, 50 and 60 cm.  (vii) Tabulate your readings.  (viii) Plot a graph with log I on the vertical axis and log V on the horizontal.  (ix) Determine the slope, s, of the graph.  (x)  Determine the intercept, c, on the vertical axis.  (xi) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results. [21 marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"x(cm)V(v)I(A)log Ilog V101.681.600.22530.2041201.701.660.23040.2201301.741.750.24050.2430401.781.800.25040.2553501.871.900.26010.2788601.901.980.27880.2967        slope, s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 0.2688\u22120.2250.29\u22120.21\\frac{0.2688-0.225}{0.29-0.21}0.29\u22120.210.2688\u22120.225\u200b = 0.04380.08\\frac{0.0438}{0.08}0.080.0438\u200b = 0.5475 = 0.55    Intercept, c = 0.1063    Precautions:  1. I ensured all terminal connections were secure and tight to prevent current fluctuations and ensure accurate readings.    2. I opened the key whenever readings were not being taken to prevent unnecessary battery drain and maintain circuit integrity.    3. I avoided parallax error by aligning my eyes directly with the scales on the ammeter and voltmeter for precise readings.    4. I placed the jockey carefully on the potentiometer wire without sliding it, to prevent wear on the wire and ensure consistent contact.    5. I verified that all measuring instruments were free from zero error before starting the experiment for increased accuracy.    6. I kept the setup on a stable surface to avoid vibrations or shifts that could affect readings.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2011>3>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2011","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CURRENT ELECTRICITY","question":"How is the brightness of the bulb affected as x increases?  Give a reason for your answer. [2 marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The brightness of the bulb increases as the length x increases. This is because as x increases, the resistance along that length also increases, reducing the current flowing through it. Consequently, more current flows through the bulb, causing it to shine brighter.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2011>3>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2011","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CURRENT ELECTRICITY~~ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CONDUCTION THROUGH MATERIALS","question":"List two electrical devices whose actions do not obey Ohm's law. [2 marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"1. Diodes: These only allow current to flow in one direction and exhibit a non-linear current-voltage relationship.    2. Transistors: Used in amplification and switching, transistors do not maintain a constant resistance, and their current-voltage behavior is non-linear.    3. Thermistors: These temperature-sensitive resistors have a resistance that varies significantly with temperature, leading to non-linear behavior.    4. Light Emitting Diodes (LEDs): LEDs have a non-linear voltage-current relationship, only conducting after reaching a threshold voltage.    5. Varistors: Varistors are used to protect circuits from voltage spikes, and their resistance changes with applied voltage.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"}];